    "category": "sql_db",
    "subcategory": "DBMS Deep",
    "question": "Explain the difference between optimistic and pessimistic concurrency control.",
    "answer": "* **Pessimistic Concurrency**: Acquires locks BEFORE accessing data. Assumes conflicts are likely. Other transactions wait.\n  - Methods: Row locks, table locks, SELECT FOR UPDATE.\n  - Pro: Guarantees no conflicts. Con: Reduced concurrency, deadlock risk.\n* **Optimistic Concurrency**: Does NOT acquire locks. Assumes conflicts are rare. At commit time, checks if data was modified by another transaction.\n  - Methods: Version numbers, timestamps. If conflict detected → transaction is retried.\n  - Pro: High concurrency, no blocking. Con: Wasted work on rollbacks if conflicts are frequent.\n* **When to use**: Pessimistic for high-contention (e.g., financial). Optimistic for low-contention (e.g., web reads).",
    "is_coding": false,
    "code_sql": "",
    "code_java": "",
