    "category": "genai_rag",
    "subcategory": "RAG & Vector Databases",
    "question": "Explain why a \"Retrieve-and-Rerank\" pattern is superior to \"Naive RAG\" in production systems.",
    "answer": "* The Problem in Naive RAG: Vector search (bi-encoders) is fast but optimized for speed over deep semantic alignment. It retrieves the top-K chunks based on cosine similarity, but the most relevant info might be ranked lower (e.g., at rank 7 instead of rank 1).\n* The Solution (Reranker): The Retrieve-and-Rerank pattern retrieves a larger number of candidates (e.g., top 25 chunks) using vector search, then passes them through a Cross-Encoder Reranker model. The reranker calculates the exact similarity between the query and each chunk in detail.\n* Benefits:\n  - Passes only the absolute best, most highly-aligned context (e.g., top 3) to the LLM.\n  - Prevents \"Lost in the Middle\" syndrome where LLMs ignore context in the middle of long prompts.\n  - Maximizes output accuracy while keeping prompt token counts low.",
    "is_coding": false,
    "code_sql": "",
    "code_java": "",
    "code_python": "",
